>{{cite book |editor1-first=Glenda |editor1-last=Rollin |editor2-first=Jack |editor2-last=Rollin |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2011\u20132012 |year=2011 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7553-6231-8 |pages=38, 274\u2013275}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10433~15093%2C00.html |title=Andrew Crofts profile |access-date=5 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905065640/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10433~15093%2C00.html |archive-date=5 September 2009 |url-status=dead }} at the Brighton & Hove Albion website\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10355~15093%2C00.html |title=Andrew Crofts profile |access-date=5 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106040921/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10355~15093%2C00.html |archive-date=6 November 2011 |url-status=dead }} at the Norwich City website\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crofts, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chatham, Kent]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Kent]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Peterborough United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wrexham A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Norwich City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scunthorpe United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Yeovil Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English footballer}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Andrew Crofts\n| image = Me and Andrew Crofts2.jpg\n| caption = Crofts with [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in 2008\n| fullname = Andrew Lawrence Crofts<ref name=\"PFA 145\">{{cite book\n| last = Hugman\n| first = Barry J.\n| title = The PFA Premier & Football League Players' Records 1946\u20132005\n| publisher = Queen Anne Press\n| year = 2005\n| page = 145\n| isbn = 978-1-85291-665-7 }}</ref>\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1984|5|29|df=y}}<ref name=\"triggs\" />\n| birth_place = [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]], England\n| currentclub = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] (player/under-23 coach)\n| clubnumber = 48\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1994\u20132000\n| youthyears2 = 2000\u20132001\n| youthclubs1 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| youthclubs2 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n| years1 = 2001\u20132009\n| years2 = 2008\u20132009\n| years3 = 2009\n| years4 = 2009\u20132010\n| years5 = 2010\u20132012\n| years6 = 2012\u20132016\n| years7 =2016\n| years8 = 2016\u20132017\n| years9= 2017\n| years10= 2018\u20132019\n| years11= 2019\n| years12= 2019\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| clubs5 = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n| clubs6 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]\n| clubs9 = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]\n| clubs10 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs11 = [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]]\n| clubs12 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| caps1 = 174\n| goals1 = 17\n| caps2 = 9\n| goals2 = 0\n| caps3 = 16\n| goals3 = 1\n| caps4 = 44\n| goals4 = 5\n| caps5 = 68\n| goals5 = 8\n| caps6 = 71\n| goals6 = 5\n| caps7 = 6\n| goals7 = 0\n| caps8 = 46\n| goals8 = 1\n| caps9= 4\n| goals9= 0\n| caps10= 9\n| goals10= 0\n| caps11= 0\n| goals11= 0\n| caps12= 0\n| goals12= 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132004\n| nationalyears2 = 2005\u20132006\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Wales national under-19 football team|Wales U19]]\n| nationalteam2 = [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales U21]]\n| nationalteam3 = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 0<ref name=\"faw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faw.org.uk/teams/1/29|title=Men \u2013 A Squad \u2013 Andrew Crofts|publisher=Football Association of Wales|accessdate=2008-09-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071229052044/http://www.faw.org.uk/teams/1/29|archivedate=29 December 2007}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps2 = 10\n| nationalgoals2 = 1<ref name=\"faw\" />\n| nationalcaps3 = 29\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| club-update =  13:15, 27 July 2019 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 07:24, 15 November 2017 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Lawrence Crofts''' (born 29 May 1984) is a professional footballer who is a player-coach for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. Reserves and Academy|Brighton & Hove Albion under-23's]]. He has made 29 appearances for [[Wales national football team|Wales]] at international level.\n\nHe started his career with Gillingham, for whom he made his [[The Football League|Football League]] debut at the age of 16, and made over 190 appearances for the [[Kent]]-based club. He had [[loan (association football)|loan]]s at [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] and [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] during the [[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309]] season and joined [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2009. After a successful season at Brighton he transferred to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in 2010, before moving back to the South Coast club in 2012.\n\nA tough-tackling midfielder, Crofts represented Wales, where one of his grandparents was born, at under-19 and under-21 level and won his first senior [[cap (sport)|cap]] in 2005. In 2008, he won his 12th cap, breaking the record for the most international caps received by a [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] player.\n\n==Early life==\nCrofts was born in [[Chatham, Kent]], and began playing competitive football at the age of six for a club in nearby [[Rainham, Kent|Rainham]]. Between the ages of 10 and 15 he attended weekly training sessions organised by [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. He also tried out on two occasions for the [[English Schools Football Association]]'s national schoolboy team, but was unsuccessful.<ref name=\"triggs\">{{cite book | first=Roger|last= Triggs | title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club| publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd | year=2001| isbn=978-0-7524-2243-5|pages=98}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Gillingham===\nIn September 2000, Crofts joined [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] as a trainee and was a regular in the club's [[youth system|youth]] and [[reserve team|reserve]] teams during the [[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301]] season. At the end of the season, shortly before his 17th birthday, he was a surprise inclusion in the [[first team]] squad for a match at home to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]],<ref name=\"triggs\" /> and made his [[The Football League|Football League]] debut as a late [[substitute (association football)|substitute]], replacing [[Marlon King]].<ref name=\"SB2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=303671|title=Gillingham 0 (0) \u2013 3 (0) Watford |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2008-09-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050827052353/http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=303671|archivedate=27 August 2005}}</ref> The following season, he suffered a broken leg during a reserve team match and missed several months of the season.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Andrew Crofts Injury Set-back \n|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~134460,00.html \n|publisher=Gillingham F.C. \n|date=1 December 2001 \n|accessdate=2008-09-25 \n|url-status=dead \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724172756/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~134460%2C00.html \n|archivedate=24 July 2011 \n}}</ref> Although he returned to action in early 2002, his next appearance for the first team did not come until October, when he came on as a substitute in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] match against [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]].<ref name=\"SB3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/MatchReport/0,,10416~21170,00.html |title=Stockport vs Gillingham 1\u20132 |publisher=Gillingham F.C. |date=1 October 2002 |accessdate=2011-11-24 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This was to be his only senior appearance of the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303]] season.<ref name=\"SB4\">{{Soccerbase season|24691|2002|name=Andrew Crofts|accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref> He finally secured a regular first team place towards the end of the following season, featuring regularly during March and April 2004.<ref name=\"SB5\">{{Soccerbase season|24691|2003|name=Andrew Crofts|accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref>\n\nCrofts was a first team regular in the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]] season, making 27 Football League appearances, and scoring his first senior goal for the club in a defeat to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 26 December.<ref name=\"SB6\">{{Soccerbase season|24691|2004|name=Andrew Crofts|accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref> In January 2005, he signed a new contract designed to keep him at the club until 2009.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football: Crofts is Top Dog for Stan\n| url = https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-127136259\n| work = Sunday Mirror\n| publisher = Findarticles|author=Peter Burrington\n| date = 16 January 2005\n| accessdate = 2008-09-29}}</ref> He was omitted from the team for most of March and April, but was recalled for the last match of the season, in which a draw with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] led to the \"Gills\" being [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] from the [[Football League Championship]], the second tier of English football, to [[Football League One]], the third tier.<ref name=\"SB6\" /><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Nottm Forest 2\u20132 Gillingham\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/4500797.stm\n| publisher= BBC Sport\n| date = 8 May 2005\n| accessdate = 2008-09-29}}</ref> In the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]] season, he made the most appearances of any player in the Gillingham squad, missing only one of the team's 46 matches in League One.<ref name=\"five\" /> Although the team struggled in the league, finishing in the lower half of the table, they defeated [[Premier League]] team [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], with Crofts scoring the winning goal.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Gillingham 3\u20132 Portsmouth (aet)\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/4258464.stm\n| work= BBC Sport\n| date = 21 September 2005\n| accessdate = 2011-11-24}}</ref><ref name=\"SB7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=154|title=Final 2005/2006 Football League One Table |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref> The following season, he again made over 40 appearances and also scored eight goals, his best total for an individual season, but Gillingham again finished the season in the bottom half of the table.<ref name=\"six\" /><ref name=\"SB8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=153|title=Final 2006/2007 Football League One Table |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref> He made his 100th start for the club on 18 December 2006 in a match against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], and marked the occasion with a goal.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football: Crofts Classic; Gillingham 1 Bournemouth 1\n| url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+CROFTS+CLASSIC%3B+Gillingham+1+Bournemouth+1.-a0155990724\n| work = Daily Mirror\n| publisher = The Free Library\n| date = 18 December 2006\n| accessdate = 2011-11-24}}</ref> At the end of the season, he won four awards at the club's Player of the Year event and was dubbed ''Mr Gillingham'' by then-manager [[Ronnie Jepson]].<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Season Review \n|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~1033690,00.html \n|publisher=Gillingham F.C. \n|date=11 June 2007 \n|accessdate=2008-09-30 \n|url-status=dead \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724172808/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~1033690%2C00.html \n|archivedate=24 July 2011 \n}}</ref> He took over as team [[Captain (association football)|captain]] in the [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]] season,<ref name=\"Gills profile\">{{cite web\n|title = Andrew Crofts\n|url = http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10416~15093,00.html\n|publisher = Gillingham F.C.\n|accessdate = 2008-09-30\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081010155328/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10416~15093%2C00.html\n|archivedate = 10 October 2008\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Gillingham 1 Albion 0\n| url = http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/1691571.Gillingham_1_Albion_0/\n| work= The Argus\n| date = 15 September 2007\n| accessdate = 2011-11-24\n| first = Andy\n| last = Naylor}}</ref> but it was an unsuccessful season for the team, who were relegated from League One.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7377686.stm|title=Leeds 2\u20131 Gillingham|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2008-05-03|date=3 May 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080505092607/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7377686.stm| archivedate= 5 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The following October he was stripped of the captaincy, which was instead given to [[Barry Fuller]]. Manager [[Mark Stimson]] stated that he felt that the captaincy might have been too much of a burden for Crofts, and had a negative effect on his form.<ref>{{cite web\n|title = Fuller handed captain's armband\n|url = http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~1415953,00.html\n|publisher = Gillingham F.C.\n|date = 8 October 2008\n|accessdate = 2008-10-08\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081010143052/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~1415953%2C00.html\n|archivedate = 10 October 2008\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref> Soon afterwards, the club made Crofts available for [[Transfer (football)|transfer]].<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Gillingham transfer-list Crofts\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/7686672.stm\n| publisher = BBC\n| date = 23 October 2008\n| accessdate = 28 October 2008 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081028025150/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/7686672.stm| archivedate= 28 October 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n====Peterborough United and Wrexham (loans)====\nIn November 2008, he joined [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] on loan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/peterborough_united/7737903.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 November 2008|date=19 November 2008|title=Crofts joins Peterborough on loan}}</ref> Shortly after returning to Gillingham the following January, he went on a second loan period, this time to [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/PressReleases/0,,10416~1560527,00.html |title=Crofts joins Wrexham on loan |publisher=Gillingham F.C. |date=17 February 2009 |accessdate=17 February 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222144920/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/PressReleases/0%2C%2C10416~1560527%2C00.html |archivedate=22 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his debut on the same day in a 2\u20131 defeat to [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/7884042.stm|title=Burton Albion 2\u20131 Wrexham|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 February 2009|accessdate=18 February 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090219195659/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/7884042.stm| archivedate= 19 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Upon his return to Gillingham from his loan spell, he was released from his contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~1667478,00.html |title=Gillingham announce retained list |publisher=Gllingham F.C. |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=1 July 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090529080326/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~1667478%2C00.html |archivedate=29 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nOn 29 June 2009, Crofts agreed to join [[Football League One|League One]] club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on a two-year contract.<ref name=\"Crofts to Sign for Albion\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1706126,00.html |title=Crofts to Sign for Albion |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=29 June 2009 |accessdate=29 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090702124331/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0%2C%2C10433~1706126%2C00.html |archivedate=2 July 2009 }}</ref> He made his debut for Brighton during the 1\u20130 home defeat to [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] on 8 August 2009<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10433~49119,00.html |title=Brighton 0\u20131 Walsall |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=8 August 2009 |accessdate=3 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105071051/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10433~49119%2C00.html |archivedate=5 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and scored his first goal for Brighton during the 2\u20132 draw at [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] on 10 October 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10433~47723,00.html |title=Yeovil Town 2\u20132 Brighton |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=10 October 2009 |accessdate=3 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105070111/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10433~47723%2C00.html |archivedate=5 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Crofts was given the role of [[Captain (association football)|captain]] by new manager [[Gus Poyet]] before the 3\u20131 away victory at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10433~48387,00.html |title=Southampton 1\u20133 Brighton |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=15 November 2009 |accessdate=3 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118035722/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10433~48387%2C00.html |archivedate=18 November 2009 }}</ref> Crofts was later confirmed as permanent captain at the beginning of January 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1921337,00.html |title=Poyet Hails Captain Marvel |date=2 January 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105040710/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0%2C%2C10433~1921337%2C00.html |archivedate=5 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Norwich City===\nOn 21 May 2010, [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] announced the acquisition of Crofts from Brighton, for an undisclosed fee, believed to be in the region of \u00a3300,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/albion/8180200.Crofts_completes_Norwich_move/|title=Crofts completes Norwich move|date=21 May 2010|publisher=The Argus|accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref> He became the club's first signing of the summer transfer window, signing a three-year deal at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~2057321,00.html |title=Crofts Joins Canaries |date=21 May 2010 |accessdate=21 May 2010 |publisher=Norwich City F.C. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524093557/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0%2C%2C10355~2057321%2C00.html |archivedate=24 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 6 August 2010, he scored a goal on his debut against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/8880936.stm|title=Norwich 2\u20133 Watford|publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 August 2010|accessdate=7 August 2010|first=Saj|last=Chowdhury| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100806193112/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/8880936.stm| archivedate= 6 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> He subsequently gained promotion to the [[Premier League]] with the \"Canaries\" in his first season at the club. He initially kept his place as a regular starter for Norwich in the top tier, but in the second half of the 2011\u201312 season he gradually fell out of favour at the club.\n\n=== Return to Brighton & Hove Albion===\nCrofts was transferred back to Brighton in August 2012.\n\n==== Loan return to Gillingham====\nOn 19 March 2016, Crofts re-joined [[Gillingham F.C|Gillingham]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35851667</ref>\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\nOn 22 July 2016, Crofts signed a one-year contract with [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=DONE DEAL: Charlton sign midfielder Andrew Crofts |url=http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/charlton-athletic-new-signing-andrew-crofts-3200477.aspx |publisher=Charlton Athletic Official Site |date=22 July 2016 |accessdate=22 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811203840/http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/charlton-athletic-new-signing-andrew-crofts-3200477.aspx |archivedate=11 August 2016 }}</ref> He scored his first goal for Charlton in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Southend United]] on 31 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38424358\n|title=Southend 1\u20131 Charlton\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=31 December 2016 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\nOn 1 September 2017 the club announced that he had ended his contract by mutual agreement.<ref>{{cite news | title = Andrew Crofts departs |url =https://www.cafc.co.uk/news/view/59a91f478527d/andrew-crofts-departs\n|publisher=Charlton Athletic Official Site |date= 1 September 2017 \n|accessdate = 1 September 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Scunthorpe United===\nCrofts signed for Scunthorpe United on 31 August 2017, signing a one-year contract with the [[North Lincolnshire]]-based club.<ref>{{cite news | title = Croats joins the Iron |url =https://www.scunthorpe-united.co.uk/news/2017/september/crofts-joins-the-iron/\n|publisher=Scunthorpe United Official Site |date= 1 September 2017 \n|accessdate = 1 September 2017 }}</ref> On 18 May 2018, he was not offered a new contract,<ref>{{cite news | title = Retained list announced |url =https://www.scunthorpe-united.co.uk/news/2018/may/retained-list-announced/\n|publisher=Scunthorpe United Official Site |date= 18 May 2018\n|accessdate = 29 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Newport County===\nOn 26 June 2018 Crofts signed for [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] on a one year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44620796|title=Andrew Crofts: Newport sign veteran Wales midfielder|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 June 2018|accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> He made his Newport debut in a 3\u20130 defeat at [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on 4 August.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44989421 Crofts debut for Newport]</ref> Crofts  was a 90th minute substitute for Newport in the [[2019 EFL League Two play-off Final|League Two playoff final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 25 May 2019. He was released by Newport at the end of the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48385544|title=Newport County release Andrew Crofts, Tyler Forbes and Will Randall|date=28 May 2019|accessdate=28 May 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Yeovil Town and second return to Brighton & Hove Albion===\nIn June 2019 Crofts joined [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] as a player-coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ytfc.net/news/2019/june/signing--crofts-joins-as-player-coach/|title=Crofts joins as player-coach|publisher=[[Yeovil Town F.C.]]|date= 27 June 2019|accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref>  On 27 July 2019, however, he left the club to rejoin [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] as a player-coach with the club's [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. Reserves and Academy|under-23 side]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/july/crofts-back-for-a-third-spell-as-coach/ |title=Crofts back for a third spell as coach |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=27 July 2019 |accessdate=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727131605/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/july/crofts-back-for-a-third-spell-as-coach/ |archive-date=27 July 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He played for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. Reserves and Academy|Brighton U21s]] in the 2\u20130 away win over [[AFC Wimbledon]] in the [[2019\u201320 EFL Trophy|EFL Trophy]] on 3 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kFTtfV-iUuM|title=AFC Wimbledon v Brighton & Hove Albion U21 highlights - YouTube |publisher=EFL |date=4 September 2019 |accessdate=4 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAs one of his grandparents was born in Wales he was eligible to play for the [[Wales national football team|Welsh national team]], and after representing the country at under-19 and under-21 level he won his first senior [[Cap (sport)|cap]], an award given to a player representing his national team, in 2005. In 2008, he won his twelfth cap, breaking the record for the [[Gillingham F.C.#International players|most international caps received by a Gillingham player]]. Crofts was selected for the [[Wales national under-19 football team|Welsh national under-19 team]] in 2002, qualifying due to having a Welsh grandparent.<ref name=\"faw\" /><ref>{{cite web\n|title=Crofts Gets Welsh Call Up \n|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~238387,00.html \n|publisher=Gillingham F.C. \n|date=12 July 2002 \n|accessdate=2008-09-25 \n|first=Amy \n|last=Inkersole \n|url-status=dead \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724172910/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~238387%2C00.html \n|archivedate=24 July 2011 \n}}</ref> He made his first appearance for the team in the [[Milk Cup]] tournament in Northern Ireland, but was forced to return home after suffering an ankle injury in the Welsh team's first match.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Andrew Crofts \u2013 Further Injury Setback \n|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~246880,00.html \n|publisher=Gillingham F.C. \n|date=30 July 2002 \n|accessdate=2008-09-25 \n|url-status=dead \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724172927/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~246880%2C00.html \n|archivedate=24 July 2011 \n}}</ref> In total he made eight appearances at under-19 level,<ref name=\"faw\" /> including appearing in a second Milk Cup in 2003.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Crofts Enjoying International Duty \n|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~401236,00.html \n|publisher=Gillingham F.C. \n|date=22 July 2003 \n|accessdate=2008-09-27 \n|url-status=dead \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724172937/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~401236%2C00.html \n|archivedate=24 July 2011 \n}}</ref>\n\nAfter moving up to the under-21 level Crofts was selected for the [[Wales national under-21 football team|national under-21 team]] for the first time for a match against [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] in February 2005.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Crofty Gets Welsh Call \n|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~619931,00.html \n|publisher=Gillingham F.C. \n|date=28 January 2005 \n|accessdate=2008-09-25 \n|url-status=dead \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724172951/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~619931%2C00.html \n|archivedate=24 July 2011 \n}}</ref> He went on to gain 12 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] at this level, scoring one goal.<ref name=\"faw\" />\n\nHe made his debut for the [[Wales national football team|Welsh national team]] against [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]] on 12 October 2005, coming on as a substitute for [[Carl Fletcher (Welsh footballer)|Carl Fletcher]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wales 2\u20130 Azerbaijan\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4324386.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 12 October 2005\n| accessdate = 2008-09-24}}</ref> At the end of the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]] season, as part of manager [[John Toshack]]'s policy of introducing young players to the team, Crofts gained two further caps, both as a substitute, against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] and [[Trinidad & Tobago national football team|Trinidad & Tobago]],<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wales 0\u20130 Paraguay\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4756204.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 1 March 2006\n| accessdate = 2008-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wales 2\u20131 Trinidad & Tobago\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/5004566.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 27 May 2006\n| accessdate = 2008-09-26}}</ref> and also played in an unofficial international match against a [[Basque Country national football team|Basque Country XI]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Basque XI 0\u20131 Wales\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/5000308.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 May 2006\n| accessdate = 2008-09-26}}</ref>\n\nHe was included in the starting line-up for an international for the first time in August 2007 when he played the full 90 minutes of a match against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]],<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Bulgaria 0\u20131 Wales: Goal makes Eastwood's day\n| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=223007&&cc=5739\n| publisher = ESPNsoccernet\n| date = 22 August 2007\n| accessdate = 2008-09-26}}</ref> but was back on the substitutes' bench for the [[UEFA Euro 2008]] qualifying match against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] the following month.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wales 0\u20132 Germany\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_of_wales/6975038.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 8 September 2007\n| accessdate = 2008-09-26}}</ref> He became established as a regular member of the Welsh squad during the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]] tournament.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|3 September 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n